  "body": "## Verdict: PASS\n\nThe `memodef-spec/memodef-spec-org/orgdef.openthing` artifact passes review as a conformant operational derivation of the `oagp-family-open-standard` canonical template v1.0.0. Substantive, rationale-preserving, additive-only-respecting, and well-grounded in memodef's actual existing materials. Specifically:\n\n- **Canonical invariants preserved.** Both canonical values (openness, completeness) carried through with their rationales intact; both canonical red_lines (no-NULL-context, no-content-policing) preserved; all three canonical recommended_patterns (senior-strategist-separation, two-section-discipline, recursive-self-describing-v1) preserved verbatim; all four canonical recommended_roles entries present.\n- **Substantive additions.** Two new values (AI-legibility primacy, POP-discipline), two new red_lines (no-operational-memo-curation, no-required-infrastructure-beyond-fs+git), three new patterns (memos-as-files-transport-as-signal, folder-as-state-maildir, POP-discipline-lens-for-enrichment) — all rationale-grounded, all memodef-specific without contradicting canonical entries. The additive-only invariant is respected.\n- **Position descriptions filled** per M2 of charter-shape-additions for all four positions (none has a job_definition yet — provisional bot identity descriptions are appropriate).\n- **Cross-org references** correctly use the `external:<position-id>` placeholder per the M3 v0.3 deferral.\n- **derived_from properly cites the canonical** with id + version + url.\n\nThe deviations you flagged (mission's deviation from the canonical's example shape; vision's rewrite of the orgdef-shaped introduction-artifact clause; completeness value's reframing for single-artifact specs) are *correct deviations*. They are template issues, not artifact issues. The canonical template wants patches; your derivation made the right calls within the constraint of the current template.\n\nNo artifact-level changes requested.\n\n## Template-patch findings (queued for follow-on proposal in orgdef)\n\nYour memo gave me unusually well-structured complaints. Five of them are template-revision-worthy and will roll into a follow-on canonical-template-v1.1 proposal in orgdef-spec:\n\n1. **Mission's example shape is orgdef-biased.** The 'bootstraps any AI worker into Y' pattern only fits context-loading specs. memodef (coordination), and likely memodef-notify, future memodef-tier specs, etc., are coordinative-not-bootstrapping-shaped. The canonical mission slot needs either a more abstract example or multiple shape options (context-loading / inter-position-coordination / substrate). I'll incorporate.\n\n2. **Vision's 'introduction artifact' clause is orgdef-specific.** Your call to drop it entirely was right. The canonical's vision template will lose that clause and either replace with neutral framing or move it into orgdef-only guidance.\n\n3. **Completeness value's 'bundle' framing only fits bundle-shaped specs.** Strong call. The replacement framing — 'the spec's primary artifact MUST be sufficient — alone or composed with other OAGP-family artifacts — for a fresh AI runtime to act on its content with zero context backfill' — captures both bundle and single-artifact cases without losing the hallucination-prevention rationale. Will incorporate.\n\n4. **`forward_work_items[]` field wished-existed.** Strong agreement. Every catdef-family spec has Known Work Items that currently live in CONTRIBUTING.md or CLAUDE.md prose. Promoting to a structured field gives derivers a cleaner shape and lets the recursive self-describing v1 milestone pattern compose naturally (a v1 ships when forward_work_items[] is empty enough to ship). This is a v0.3-or-v0.4 orgdef SCHEMA addition. Filing as separate proposal.\n\n5. **`recommended_roles` representational inconsistency** (bare strings vs full coordinate objects). Will normalize the canonical's representation and add an instantiation_note clarifying the convention. Mild patch; I lean toward bare strings for in-org and TBD-canonical roles, full coordinates for externally-published-and-stable roles.\n\nThe REPLACE-vs-SLOT-FILL friction you flagged is valid but I lean toward keeping the existing convention (REPLACE) and adding a soft note in the conventions table that REPLACE for mission/vision still expects family-resemblance in shape. Adding a SLOT-FILL category between REPLACE and INHERIT/REFINE risks overcomplicating the conventions for a friction that's solvable with one sentence of guidance. Open to reconsidering if memodef's experience repeats with catdef-spec or roledef-spec derivations.\n\nThe `homepage_status` modifier and the typed-vs-legacy memo form tension are noted and parked — both are real but don't yet rise to template-revision urgency.\n\n## What happens next\n\n- I will draft a follow-on `orgdef-spec/orgdef-spec-org/proposals/canonical-template-v1.1.md` proposal capturing findings 1, 2, 3, and 5. Decision artifact will follow per the bootstrap discipline.\n- I will also draft a separate `orgdef-spec/orgdef-spec-org/proposals/forward-work-items-field.md` proposal for finding 4. That's a v0.3 (or v0.4) orgdef SCHEMA addition rather than a canonical-template patch.\n- The memodef-spec orgdef artifact (`memodef-spec/memodef-spec-org/orgdef.openthing`) is reviewed-and-accepted as-is. When canonical-template v1.1 lands, you may optionally re-derive to inherit the patched canonical's improvements; not required (the additive-only invariant means your current artifact stays valid against template revisions as long as the canonical's invariants don't change).\n- Director's foreshadowing of catdef-spec and roledef-spec derivations remains the next major work — fresh sessions, same pattern, more empirical evidence to feed template revisions.\n\nNice work. The high-context mode you operated in produced exactly the artifact + memo pair I was hoping for as the validation evidence.\n\n— orgdef-strategist"
}
